\code{eberhart_russell()} implements the classic joint regression model proposed by
Eberhart and Russell (1966) to evaluate phenotypic stability and adaptability
across multi-environment trials (MET).

The model partitions the genotype-environment (GxE) interaction into a linear
response to an environmental index (adaptability, \eqn{b_1}) and non-linear
deviations from the regression line (stability, \eqn{s^2_{di}}).

The phenotypic mean of genotype \eqn{i} in environment \eqn{j} is modeled as:
\deqn{Y_{ij} = b_0 + b_1 I_j + \delta_{ij} + \bar{\varepsilon}_{ij}}

Where:
\itemize{
\item \eqn{Y_{ij}} is the mean performance of genotype \eqn{i} in environment \eqn{j}.
\item \eqn{b_0} is the intercept (general mean of genotype \eqn{i}).
\item \eqn{b_1} is the regression coefficient (slope), measuring phenotypic response/adaptability.
\item \eqn{I_j} is the environmental index of site \eqn{j}, computed as \eqn{I_j = \bar{Y}_{.j} - \bar{Y}_{..}}.
\item \eqn{\delta_{ij}} represents the deviation from the regression of genotype \eqn{i} in environment \eqn{j}.
\item \eqn{\bar{\varepsilon}_{ij}} is the pooled experimental error associated with the cell mean.
}
}
\details{
Two critical statistical tests are executed for each genotype:
\enumerate{
\item A \strong{Student's t-test} under \eqn{H_0: b_1 = 1} to assess if the genotype's
response tracks the exact population average (\eqn{b_1 > 1} indicates response to premium environments;
\eqn{b_1 < 1} indicates resistance/predictability in poor environments).
\item An \strong{F-test} under \eqn{H_0: s^2_{di} = 0} using the pooled experimental error
as the denominator. Significantly high deviations indicate poor stability (low predictability).
}
